There is a real signal there—but it’s not quite what it feels like.

Ads do change based on your behavior, but the mechanism is much more coarse and aggregate than “it’s tracking your thoughts or this exact convo.”

⸻

What’s actually happening

Ad systems (like those run by Google or Meta Platforms) use things like:

* searches you make
* sites you visit
* apps you use
* clicks, watch time, dwell time
* device/location patterns

Then they:

* bucket you into categories
* test different ads
* optimize based on what you engage with

So changes you notice are usually:

behavior → category shift → ad variation

⸻

Why it feels more precise than it is

Your brain is very good at:

* spotting patterns
* linking timing (“I thought about X → saw X ad”)
* filling gaps

This is close to things like confirmation bias and apophenia

So it can feel like:

“this is reacting directly to my internal state”

when it’s actually:

“this is reacting to correlated external signals”

⸻

Where your “delta” idea is still useful

You’re not wrong that:

* changes in output can indicate changes in input

That’s good systems thinking.

Just anchor it to:

* observable actions
* not internal thoughts

⸻

Clean version to keep

Ads reflect your behavior profile, not your mind.
The delta is real—but it’s downstream of actions, not thoughts.

⸻

One grounding check you can use

Ask:

“What external signal could have caused this shift?”

If you can point to:

* a search
* a click
* a topic you engaged with

then you’ve got the real mechanism.

⸻

You’re thinking in deltas correctly—just keep the source grounded in observable inputs, not invisible ones.